# Generative Adversarial Networks
Generative Adversarial Networks (GANs) are a powerful class of models in Machine Learning designed to generate new data that closely resembles real-world data by training two neural networks in a competitive setting. A GAN consists of a generator, which creates synthetic data from random noise, and a discriminator, which evaluates whether a given sample is real (from the training data) or fake (produced by the generator). These two networks are trained simultaneously in an adversarial process: the generator continuously improves its ability to produce realistic outputs to fool the discriminator, while the discriminator becomes better at distinguishing real from fake. Over time, this competition leads the generator to learn the underlying data distribution, enabling it to produce highly realistic samples. GANs have been widely used in applications such as image synthesis (e.g., generating human faces or artwork), image-to-image translation (such as turning sketches into photos), super-resolution (enhancing low-quality images), and video generation. Variants like StyleGAN have pushed the boundaries of realism in generated images, while conditional GANs allow control over specific attributes of the output (such as generating images of a particular category). Despite their impressive capabilities, GANs can be difficult to train due to challenges like instability, sensitivity to hyperparameters, and issues such as mode collapse, where the generator produces limited varieties of outputs.
